<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0847-A"><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev Tuesday refused to resign and annul the results of a disputed parliamentary election, saying that talks were the only way out of the crisis.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="6" sums="11,29,37,41,43,6"><scu uid="87" label="Akayev refused to step down." weight="2"/><scu uid="91" label="Akayev said talks were the solution to the crisis." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050321.0354"><line>The news agency quoted him as saying: &quot;The events now include unlawful actions, massive demonstrations, attacks on representatives of law enforcement agencies who are carrying out their duties.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050323.0237"><line>Seghizbayev said Akayev had named the security chief of his administration, Murat Sutalinov, as the new chief prosecutor, and Bishkek police chief Keneshbek Dushebayev as interior minister.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>&quot;Mass violations began already began this morning... the election race was untransparent, there were mass violations (and) huge use of administrative resources&quot; to affect the outcome of the vote, Otunybayeva said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050316.0396"><line>They rallied, blocked roads and occupied several government buildings, demanding Akayev's resignation.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="20,41"><scu uid="70" label="The opposition blocked roads." weight="3"/><scu uid="71" label="The opposition occupied government buildings." weight="3"/><scu uid="84" label="The opposition demanded Akayev's resignation" weight="2"/><scu uid="84" label="The opposition demanded Akayev's resignation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>If he does, it will be be a first for the region, as no president has so far ever stood down at elections in the former Soviet Central Asian republics of Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>The opposition refused to accept the results and accused the authorities of fraud in the election.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050302.0275"><line>The polls are being closely watched as a stepping stone to October 30 presidential polls at which President Askar Akayev has vowed to stand down -- a promise that some opposition figures distrust.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>Akayev insisted Sunday that there would be no attempt to change the constitution to give him a new term in office, as opponents have suspected.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="83" label="The opposition feared Akayev's reign might be extended." weight="2"/><scu uid="95" label="Akayev promised to step down in October." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050316.0396"><line>On Monday in the western Talas region, the opposition even took hostage a regional governor and a district chief.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>Voting equipment being used such as indelible ink for marking voters' fingers to ensure they vote only once and transparent ballot boxes &quot;are all recognised as ensuring fair and honest elections,&quot; the Kyrgyz leader said after casting his vote in the capital Bishkek.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Among those detained was the meeting's organizer, Bolot Maripov, who had unsuccessfully run against Akayev's daughter, Bermet Akayeva.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>&quot;President Akayev has always cared about the people and the country's well-being,&quot; Vyacheslav Krasiyenko, a high school principal, said at the assembly.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>Kyrgyz Prime Minister Nikolai Tanayev vowed late on Sunday to seek negotiations to solve the dispute with the opposition over the country's recent parliamentary elections, said news from Kyrgyz capital Bishkek.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="10,19,21,32,43,49,57"><scu uid="91" label="Akayev said talks were the solution to the crisis." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050302.0275"><line>Western observers have strongly criticized the polls' standards, alleging violations by the election's administrators and dubious court decisions disqualifying several candidates.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="68" label="Western observers cited mass election violations." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>Akayev, who has been in power since before the 1991 Soviet Union collapse, has publicly pledged to hold the presidential election according to the constitution, which restricts the president to two consecutive terms.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050323.0237"><line>Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev fired the interior minister and prosecutor-general on Wednesday, his spokesman said, as a wave of opposition protests across the south kept up pressure on his government.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="5" sums="30,36,37,55,6"><scu uid="79" label="Akayev fired the interior minister." weight="3"/><scu uid="80" label="Akayev fired the prosecutor general." weight="3"/><scu uid="70" label="The opposition blocked roads." weight="3"/><scu uid="71" label="The opposition occupied government buildings." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>But prominent opposition leader Roza Otunbayeva of the Ata-Jurt (Homeland) coalition said that &quot;mass violations&quot; had already occurred and called on Akayev to sack officials in his administration who she accused of orchestrating a signature-gathering campaign aimed at getting constitutional changes allowing Akayev to remain in office.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>However Akayev has so far not cracked down on the foreign non-governmental organisations that some leaders in the region have blamed for Ukraine's and Georgias popular movements that voted down the old guard there.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050321.0354"><line>The ITAR-TASS news agency quoted Akayev as saying that he belived, however, that voting had been carried out &quot;strictly according to the law.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>&quot;We cannot put the legitimacy of newly-elected deputies in doubt just because someone wants it so,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>Last month, the new leaders of Ukraine and Georgia denied that foreign interference sparked the &quot;people power&quot; movements in the ex-Soviet nations.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>At least four policemen were reported beaten to death Sunday in clashes that broke out after police fired shots but failed to stop the demonstrations.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>Hundreds of opposition activists rallied in the Kyrgyz capital Saturday to urge President Askar Akayev to step down at the end of his term in October, amid fears he might try and hold onto power.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="14,22,25,3,35,44,49,51,8"><scu uid="59" label="President Akayev was urged to step down at the end of October" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>Thousands of opposition supporters, angered at what they say rigged elections, stormed government buildings in the southern Kyrgyz town of Jalal-Abad on Sunday, following protests Friday in nearby Osh.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="67" label="The opposition charged the government with mass election violations" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050323.0237"><line>Protesters this week seized control of government buildings in two of Kyrgyzstan's seven regional capitals and a number of smaller locales.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050321.0354"><line>&quot;Today President Akayev met with the chairman of the central election commission and the chairman of the supreme court,&quot; his spokesman Abdil Segizbayev told AFP by telephone.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>The activists passed a resolution that called for the government to ensure that this year's parliamentary and presidential elections meet democratic standards.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>&quot;Only the people can make such a decision.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050323.0237"><line>The protests began after the first round of parliamentary elections on Feb. 27 and swelled after March 13 run-offs that the opposition and the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe said were seriously flawed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>Akayev is officially serving his second term.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Some 300 supporters of a candidate who lost his bid for a parliament seat to the daughter of Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev gathered in central Bishkek, in the words of one, to &quot;hold a peaceful meeting to defend freedom of speech and honest elections.&quot;<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="0,9"><scu uid="63" label="Opposition activists demonstrated in favor of democratric elections." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>&quot;We categorically deny that these democratic and peaceful revolutions were instigated artificially or through external influence,&quot; Ukraine's Viktor Yushchenko and Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili said in a joint statement.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>&quot;I believe these elections will be successful,&quot; Akayev said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="18,47"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>The opposition rallied, blocked roads and occupied several government buildings, demanding Akayev's resignation.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="20,41"><scu uid="70" label="The opposition blocked roads." weight="3"/><scu uid="71" label="The opposition occupied government buildings." weight="3"/><scu uid="84" label="The opposition demanded Akayev's resignation" weight="2"/><scu uid="84" label="The opposition demanded Akayev's resignation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>Meanwhile, hundreds of delegates to the Kyrgyzstan People's Assembly also gathered in Bishkek Saturday to praise Akayev's achievements during his 15 years in power.</line><line>Akayev is one of the most liberal leaders in formerly Soviet Central Asia but he has drawn increased criticism in recent years for alleged attempts to tighten control.</line><line>Kyrgyzstan is scheduled to hold parliamentary elections on Feb. 27, setting the stage for a presidential vote in October.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"><scu uid="62" label="Kyrgyz parliamentary elections were held on Feb. 27, 2005" weight="2"/><scu uid="77" label="Kyrgyz presidential elections were planned for October." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050316.0396"><line>Akayev has served the maximum two terms allowed by the constitution and has pledged to step down before the presidential election scheduled for October.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="66" label="The Kyrgyz constitution limits the president to two terms." weight="3"/><scu uid="95" label="Akayev promised to step down in October." weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev on Wednesday blamed the opposition leaders for inciting a civil war, said news from Bishkek, capital of the former Soviet republic.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="19" sums="11,13,14,18,19,20,21,22,23,25,30,32,36,41,43,44,48,51,57"><scu uid="89" label="Akayev said the opposition was inciting civil war." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Maritov is also the founder of a respected daily in the Kyrgyz capital, Obshchestvennoye Mneniye.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>The prime minister said he had contacted the opposition leader in the current parliament and reaffirmed the government's stances, hoping that the opposition enters the country's leadership through legal procedures.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>&quot;I don't plan to introduce constitutional changes -- today we have the ideal and optimal constitution and balance of power,&quot; Akayev said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050323.0237"><line>Akayev spokesman Abdil Seghizbayev said that officially, Interior Minister Bakirdin Subanbekov and Prosecutor-General Myktybek Abdyldayev were dismissed at their own request, but that the dismissals were linked &quot;to the events in the south and their poor work on preventing those events.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>The delegates condemned the opposition and said Akayev was responsible for bringing stability and economic growth in 2004.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050316.0396"><line>The opposition, who were defeated in the runoff of the country' s parliamentary elections, made &quot;provocative cries intended to plunge us all into illegality and the abyss of civil war and inter- ethnic conflict,&quot; Akayev said on state television.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="89" label="Akayev said the opposition was inciting civil war." weight="1"/><scu uid="93" label="The opposition was defeated in the March run-off parliamentary elections." weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>The opposition refused to accept the results and accused the authorities of fraud in the election.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="67" label="The opposition charged the government with mass election violations" weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>The opposition leaders &quot;have thrown off their democratic masks and have openly begun calling for the authorities' overthrow,&quot; said the president.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>&quot;There wont be any kind of revolution or upheaval of course, there are no reasons for that, but we should be ready to strongly resist various attempts to introduce discord and upheaval or to commit disorder,&quot; said Askar Akayev, who has been in power here since Kyrgyzstan became independent from Moscow in 1991 with the end of the Soviet Union.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>The parliamentary elections, which are a stepping stone to presidential elections on October 30, have been surrounded by controversy, with protests in several parts of this mountainous country in the days leading up to the vote.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>The president of the central Asian state of Kyrgyzstan Tuesday put fellow citizens on guard against a pre-election &quot;revolutionary virus,&quot; in an apparent reference to recent events in two other former Soviet republics, Ukraine and Georgia.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="10,16,21,33,40,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050321.0354"><line>&quot;He ordered them to carry out an investigation into all instances of violations that occurred in the election process,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>Akayev has blamed the opposition leaders for inciting a civil war.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="18,20,21,37,43,49,6"><scu uid="89" label="Akayev said the opposition was inciting civil war." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050302.0275"><line>A protest in southern Kyrgyzstan over a dispute March 13.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="23"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050321.0354"><line>Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev on Monday ordered authorities in the central Asian nation to investigate charges of fraud in a recent parliamentary poll that sparked a series of opposition protests in the country's volatile south.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="10" sums="11,12,13,14,23,30,36,41,42,44"><scu uid="78" label="Akayev ordered investigations into the fraud charges." weight="3"/><scu uid="70" label="The opposition blocked roads." weight="3"/><scu uid="71" label="The opposition occupied government buildings." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>Akayev has served the maximum two terms allowed by the constitution and has pledged to step down before the presidential election scheduled for October.</line><line>Tanayev said President Askar Akayev and himself were ready to have negotiations with the opposition at any time.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="16,20,22,25,29,37,5,51,55"><scu uid="91" label="Akayev said talks were the solution to the crisis." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Kyrgyz police dispersed an opposition rally in the capital Wednesday as unrest over a parliamentary election dominated by pro-presidential forces simmered for a second week, according to an AFP reporter on the scene.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="0,9"><scu uid="64" label="Akayev won a landslide parliamentary victory." weight="4"/><scu uid="81" label="Police dispersed crowds in Bishkek" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>Kyrgyzstan's President Askar Akayev insisted that voting in crucial parliamentary elections in the former Soviet republic on Sunday was being conducted fairly, but a leading opposition figure cried foul.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="5" sums="23,29,3,35,57"><scu uid="67" label="The opposition charged the government with mass election violations" weight="4"/><scu uid="88" label="Akayev said that the elections were fair." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050316.0396"><line>Akayev's supporters won a landslide victory in the parliament elections held on Feb. 27 with runoffs in many regions on March 13.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="64" label="Akayev won a landslide parliamentary victory." weight="4"/><scu uid="62" label="Kyrgyz parliamentary elections were held on Feb. 27, 2005" weight="2"/><scu uid="92" label="Run-off parliamentary elections were held in many regions on 13 March." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>Critics, however, fear that Akayev's supporters will try to hold a referendum to extend his term or that he will try to hand-pick a successor.</line><line>Around 300 people organized by a coalition of civic groups gathered near Bishkek's Victory Square, holding signs and placards.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>Kyrgyzstan, a mountainous country of around five million people, hosts Russian and US airforce units at separate bases, the latter used by Washington for operations in Afghanistan.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>The assembly is a government-orchestrated event meant to represent all regions and ethnicities in Kyrgyzstan.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050321.0014"><line>Akayev's supporters won a landslide victory in the parliament elections held on Feb. 27 with runoffs in many regions on March 13.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>&quot;The country is in danger today -- they've closed down all the press, we are totally closed... it's the government which wants to destabilise the situation,&quot; Otunbayeva told journalists.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Police detained some of the demonstrators after dispersing the gathering, witnesses said.</line><line>The demonstrators had intended to march onto the seat of the government and the presidency.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050227.0055"><line>Sunday's elections were closely watched, partly because Akayev's promises to stand down could be a first for the Central Asian former Soviet republics, where no national leader has stood down in polls since the end of Soviet rule in 1991.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="95" label="Akayev promised to step down in October." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>Russia accused the United States of instigating the protests, which replaced Moscow-friendly regimes with pro-Western leaders.</line><line>The Kyrgyz polls are being closely watched because Akayev has vowed to stand down in October.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="13,32,43,47"><scu uid="95" label="Akayev promised to step down in October." weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Akayev was speaking ahead of Kyrgyz parliamentary elections on February 27 that will set the stage for presidential polls on October 30.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="9" sums="12,25,3,32,35,40,42,49,51"><scu uid="62" label="Kyrgyz parliamentary elections were held on Feb. 27, 2005" weight="2"/><scu uid="77" label="Kyrgyz presidential elections were planned for October." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>&quot;There isn't and cannot be a resolution of the issue by force,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>A son and daughter of Akayev are both standing in the elections to the 75-seat parliament.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050205.0266"><line>&quot;The president must provide conditions for free and fair elections for all candidates for president and pass his authority to a winner of the (presidential) election,&quot; the resolution said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>Opposition supporters in Kyrgyzstan have held protests for more than a week since a March 13 run-off election that saw the opposition presence in the 75-member parliament reduced to a mere handful of seats.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>Observers say Akayev is anxious that power should pass to persons who will not turn against the current first family, which has extensive business interests.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>&quot;As regards my resignation, the issue is outside the competence of meetings or political forces,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>&quot;Internal and external attempts of this type can... at a time of large-scale political election campaigning, create additional opportunities for extremist forces to spread the pernicious viruses of discord and conflict,&quot; Akayev said on state television.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050322.0433"><line>&quot;It's obvious that there is no basis and thus there cannot be any talk of an annullment of the parliamentary elections,&quot; Akayev was reported as saying by news agencies in a televised address to his central Asian nation.</line><line>&quot;All problems must be decided through a political route, by talks.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050323.0268"><line>The police were not reported to have used excessive force.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050208.0580"><line>Like other leaders in the region Akayev has repeatedly voiced anxiety at recent popular opposition to the post-Soviet old guard in Georgia and Ukraine, where more western-oriented leaders have come to power.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,40,5"/></line></document></collection>